cleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1111/1475-6773.12872</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC6232402</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">29756355</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">40446184</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>07</Month><Day>16</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>10</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1527-7755</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>43</Volume><Issue>21</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Jul</Month><Day>20</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of clinical oncology : official journal of the American Society of Clinical Oncology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Clin Oncol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Five-Year Survival Outcomes With Atezolizumab After Chemotherapy in Resected Stage IB-IIIA Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer (IMpower010): An Open-Label, Randomized, Phase III Trial.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>2343</StartPage><EndPage>2349</EndPage><MedlinePgn>2343-2349</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1200/JCO-24-01681</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>IMpower010 (ClinicalTrials.gov identifier: NCT02486718) previously showed that atezolizumab improved disease-free survival (DFS) versus best supportive care (BSC) after adjuvant chemotherapy in patients with resected non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC). We report DFS final analysis, second overall survival (OS) interim analysis, and safety with a &#x2265;5-year follow-up. Patients with completely resected stage IB-IIIA NSCLC were randomly assigned to atezolizumab (1,200 mg once every 3 weeks, 16 cycles) or BSC after platinum-based chemotherapy. At clinical cutoff (January 26, 2024), stratified hazard ratios (HRs; 95% CI) for DFS were 0.85 (95% CI, 0.71 to 1.01; <i>P</i> = .07) in the intention-to-treat (n = 1,005), 0.83 (95% CI, 0.69 to 1.00) in the all-randomized stage II-IIIA (n = 882), and 0.70 (95% CI, 0.55 to 0.91) in stage II-IIIA PD-L1 tumor cell (TC) &#x2265;1% (n = 476) populations. Stratified HRs (95% CI) for OS were 0.97 (95% CI, 0.78 to 1.22), 0.94 (95% CI, 0.75 to 1.19), and 0.77 (95% CI, 0.56 to 1.06), respectively. The unstratified HRs (95% CI) in the stage II-IIIA PD-L1 TC &#x2265;50% population (n = 229) were 0.48 (95% CI, 0.32 to 0.72) for DFS and 0.47 (95% CI, 0.28 to 0.77) for OS, and the unstratified HRs in the stage II-IIIA PD-L1 TC &#x2265;50% without <i>EGFR</i>/<i>ALK</i> alterations (n = 209) population were 0.49 (95% CI, 0.32 to 0.75) and 0.44 (95% CI, 0.26 to 0.74). No new safety signals were reported. IMpower010 is the first study to report survival outcomes with a &#x2265;5-year follow-up and continued to show benefit with atezolizumab versus BSC after adjuvant chemotherapy in patients with resected stage II-IIIA PD-L1-selected NSCLC.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Felip</LastName><ForeName>Enriqueta</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-7620-0098</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Vall d'Hebron University Hospital, Vall d'Hebron Institute of Oncology (VHIO), Barcelona, Spain.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Altorki</LastName><ForeName>Nasser</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-9754-9945</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital, Weill Cornell Medicine, New York, NY.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhou</LastName><ForeName>Caicun</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-1072-9941</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Oncology, Tongji University Affiliated Shanghai Pulmonary Hospital, Shanghai, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo